1) Learn how computers, the internet, and operating systems work so you understand the environment your code runs in.
2) Pick one beginner-friendly programming language and learn the basics of variables, loops, functions, and data types.
3) Practice writing small programs until you feel comfortable solving simple problems using code.
4) Learn Git so you can track changes, collaborate with others, and publish your code online.
5) Study essential data structures and algorithms to improve your problem-solving and technical interview skills.
6) Choose a backend technology and learn to build APIs that send, store, and process data.
7) Learn SQL and understand how relational databases store, retrieve, and manipulate data.
8) Study frontend development so you can build interactive user interfaces that connect to your backend.
9) Learn software engineering best practices like clean code, testing, and common design patterns that make code maintainable.
10) Explore DevOps fundamentals so you understand how to deploy, containerize, and manage applications in real environments.
11) Study system design concepts so you can understand how large-scale, real-world systems are built and how they scale.
12) Pick a specialization that matches your interests and go deeper into the technologies used in that field.
13) Build a strong portfolio of real projects, prepare for interviews, and practice consistently to become job-ready.